  "prompt": "What is the electric potential at the centre of sphere?",
  "response": "The electric potential at the center of a sphere depends on the charge distribution within the sphere. Here are two common cases:\n\n### 1. **Conducting Sphere (with a charged shell):**\n   - If the sphere is a **conducting sphere** with a total charge \\( Q \\) distributed uniformly on its surface, the electric potential at **any point inside the sphere (including the center)** is the same as the potential at the surface. This is because the electric field inside a conductor in electrostatic equilibrium is zero, and the potential is constant throughout.\n   - The potential at the center (and everywhere inside) is given by:\n     \\[\n     V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R}\n     \\]\n     where:\n     - \\( Q \\) = total charge on the sphere,\n     - \\( R \\) = radius of the sphere,\n     - \\( \\epsilon_0 \\) = permittivity of free space.\n\n### 2. **Uniformly Charged Solid Sphere:**\n   - If the sphere is a **solid sphere** with a uniform volume charge density \\( \\rho \\), the potential at the center can be calculated by integrating the contributions from all the charges in the sphere.\n   - The potential at the center is given by:\n     \\[\n     V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{3Q}{2R}\n     \\]\n     where:\n     - \\( Q \\) = total charge of the sphere,\n     - \\( R \\) = radius of the sphere,\n     - \\( \\epsilon_0 \\) = permittivity of free space.\n\n### Summary:\n   - For a **conducting sphere**, \\( V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R} \\),\n   - For a **solid sphere with uniform charge distribution**, \\( V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{3Q}{2R} \\).\n\nLet me know if you need further clarification!",
